  "texts": [
    "This is rather counterintuitive at a first glance but can be explained using nuclear structure considerations.",
    "In fact, the 96 Zr nucleus was predicted to be larger than 96 Ru because of its thicker neutron skin, resulting in a slightly smaller energy density and fewer particles being produced in Zr+Zr than in Ru+Ru collisions [139][140][141].",
    "The larger 96 Zr nucleus also provides smaller eccentricity at a given centrality and thus smaller v 2 [139, 140].",
    "Although the non-identical v 2 is properly con- sidered in the blind analysis observable Δ ∕v 2, non-iden- tical event multiplicities are not.",
    "After properly factoring Fig. 17 (Color online) The Δ correlators as functions of multiplicity in p+Pb and Pb+Pb collisions from the LHC compact moon solenoid (CMS) [129] (left) and in p/d+Au and Au+Au collisions from RHIC STAR [130] (right) in the multiplicity, the isobar ratios of NΔ ∕v 2 from vari- ous analyses shown in Fig."
  ]
